<subSubSection id="2FDE6573C0612B1CFF30FEBDE136FDDE" pageId="4" pageNumber="39" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="677B36F8C0612B1CFF30FEBDE7D7FE49" blockId="4.[151,1436,151,611]" pageId="4" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis id="55B0EAEAC0612B1CFF30FEBDE22CFEFC" bold="true" box="[199,315,295,320]" pageId="4" pageNumber="39">Remarks.</emphasis>
The test of adult 
<taxonomicName id="A0C44D7BC0612B1CFDF6FEB3E196FEFC" baseAuthorityName="Audouin" baseAuthorityYear="1809" box="[513,641,297,320]" class="Echinoidea" family="Diadematidae" genus="Diadema" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diadematoida" pageId="4" pageNumber="39" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="savignyi">
<emphasis id="55B0EAEAC0612B1CFDF6FEB3E196FEFC" box="[513,641,297,320]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="39">D. savignyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from that of adult 
<taxonomicName id="A0C44D7BC0612B1CFBB5FEB3E7A9FEFC" baseAuthorityName="Leske" baseAuthorityYear="1778" box="[1090,1214,297,320]" class="Echinoidea" family="Diadematidae" genus="Diadema" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diadematoida" pageId="4" pageNumber="39" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="setosum">
<emphasis id="55B0EAEAC0612B1CFBB5FEB3E7A9FEFC" box="[1090,1214,297,320]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="39">D. setosum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
because the former has up to five primary tubercles in one horizontal series in the interambulacra, and the latter has six to seven. In life, 
<taxonomicName id="A0C44D7BC0612B1CFF3CFEEBE25BFE34" baseAuthorityName="Audouin" baseAuthorityYear="1809" box="[203,332,369,392]" class="Echinoidea" family="Diadematidae" genus="Diadema" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diadematoida" pageId="4" pageNumber="39" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="savignyi">
<emphasis id="55B0EAEAC0612B1CFF3CFEEBE25BFE34" box="[203,332,369,392]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="39">D. savignyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
lacks a red ring around the anus, but has bright blue lines around the plates in the apical system, and two paired, thin lines of the same vivid color running down along each interradial suture towards a white, iridescent spot. At this point, the two blue lines diverge to run along the center of each column of interambulacral plates. In 
<taxonomicName id="A0C44D7BC0612B1CFEF3FE47E293FE48" baseAuthorityName="Audouin" baseAuthorityYear="1809" box="[260,388,477,500]" class="Echinoidea" family="Diadematidae" genus="Diadema" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diadematoida" pageId="4" pageNumber="39" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="savignyi">
<emphasis id="55B0EAEAC0612B1CFEF3FE47E293FE48" box="[260,388,477,500]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="39">D. savignyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, right blue lines can often be seen around the bases of the primary spines.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="677B36F8C0612B1CFF30FD98E136FDDE" blockId="4.[151,1436,151,611]" pageId="4" pageNumber="39">
<bibRefCitation id="03554B09C0612B1CFF30FD98E24CFDA7" author="Clark, H. L." box="[199,347,514,539]" pageId="4" pageNumber="39" pagination="83 - 102" refId="ref9242" refString="Clark, H. L. (1915) The echinoderms of Ceylon other than holothurians. Spolia Zeylanica, 10, 83 - 102." type="journal article" year="1915">Clark (1915)</bibRefCitation>
reported this species in 
<collectingCountry id="1FD37668C0612B1CFD73FD98E1E1FDA7" box="[644,758,514,539]" name="Sri Lanka" pageId="4" pageNumber="39">Sri Lanka</collectingCountry>
for the first time based on two specimens housed at the Colombo Museum. However, no exact locality nor depth records are available. Clark’s collection is no longer available at the Colombo Museum.
</paragraph>
